<TITLE> Indian gold demand down as buyers wait out </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MUMBAI, June 13 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - India's demand for gold remained low though prices fell on Wednesday with buyers in no hurry to acquire stocks in the lean season, dealers said. "People are watching the rupee go up and down," said Prithviraj Kothari, director at Riddisiddhi Bullions Ltd, a large Mumbai-based wholesaler. "Demand is very slow." Though demand was unlikely to pick up before August, when festivals start, a dip to 8,500 rupees per 10 grams may be seen as too-good-to-resist, said Kothari. Dealers in banks, who are the primary sellers of gold, echoed the same sentiment. "Gold's fallen since the morning (overseas), but look at the rupee... it is keeping it propped up," said a dealer. The Indian rupee had an early low of 40.90 to a dollar, but weakened on dollar purchases from importers. Overseas gold was down on the back of the dollar strengthening against the euro and the yen, with rising US bond yields boosting its allure
